CHILE DAYBOOK: Central Bank President, Finance Minister Speak

-- B y   R a n d y   W o o d s
-- 
2011-04-14T03:00:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-14/chile-daybook-central-bank-president-finance-minister-speak.html
Chile ’s central bank President Jose De Gregorio speaks at a Goldman Sachs Group Inc. conference in
 New York . Finance Minister Felipe Larrain speaks at Adolfo
Ibanez University, while NYSE Euronext Executive Vice President
Scott Cutler speaks to reporters at 8:30 a.m. New York time.  ECONOMY:
Chile’s central bank will raise its benchmark interest rate to
5.75 percent in six months, according to the median estimate of
traders and investors in a bi-weekly central bank survey.
Consumer prices probably will rise 0.4 percent this month from
March and 4.3 percent in 12 months, the survey showed.  EQUITIES:
The Ipsa index rose 0.6 percent to 4,645.17, ending a four-day
losing streak.
Banco de Chile rose 2.7 percent to 67.69 pesos, the steepest
gain in two weeks. Chile’s second-largest lender by assets
posted preliminary profit of 117 billion pesos ($248 million) in
the first quarter, according to a statement on its website.
Cencosud SA gained 1.7 percent to 3,389 pesos. Latin America’s
third-largest retailer by sales recovered some of the ground
lost in a 4.8 percent decline yesterday when it announced plans
to sell up to $2 billion in new shares within the next three
years to fund acquisitions. Cencosud was rated “undervalued”
in new coverage at Banco Penta.  MARKETS:
Chilean interest-rate swaps climbed after traders increased bets
on a third straight half-point rate increase next month after
the central bank lifted borrowing costs. The six-month swap rate
in pesos increased eight basis points, or 0.08 percentage point,
to 5.31 percent.
Chile’s peso gained 0.4 percent to 472.16 per  U.S. dollar  from
473.86. The central bank paid an average of 473.48 pesos per
dollar for $50 million.
The five-year swap rate in pesos increased two basis points to
6.06 percent, according to data compiled by Bloomberg.
The central bank sold 48.3 billion pesos ($102 million) of bonds
due in two and five years at a yield of 6.02 percent and 6.38
percent, respectively.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
